title: For Sale/Trade:  218 Bee casings & dies
postcontent: Contact me if you have any interest in 218 Bee brass. I have 50 casings that have been fired not cleaned, 239 that are clean and primed and 100 that are new brass. Also have the die set.History, Details, Ballistics, and Drop for the .218 BeeCartridge Type: RifleHeight: 1.345"Width: 0.408"Average FPS: 2760Average Energy: 778Average Gr: 46Recoil: 0.56Power Rank: 1.27 of 20 [?] The .218 Bee was designed in 1938 by manufacturer Winchester and is based off the .32-20 Winchester cartridge. The .218 was first introduced in 1938 for the Model 65 lever action rifle. The ballistic performance based off the 35, 40, 46, and 50 grain are 3,205 ft/s (35 gr), 3,130 ft/s (40 gr), 2,708 ft/s (46 gr), and 2,654 ft/s (50 gr). The bullet was designed for lever actions rifles by lowering the neck of the .25-20 Winchester to accept the .224 bullet shell.The .218 Bee bullet was designed for varmint hunting back in 1938, but lacked popularity when it entered the market during 1939, and never gained any traction compared to others such as the .22 Hornet. It was originally made for the Model 65 lever action rifles that were based off the 1892 versions. The .218 Bee is compared to the .22 Hornet, and has a higher velocity along with a higher maximum effective range. The .218 Bee is considered accurate up to 200 yards for varmints and 150 yards for small game such as coyote.

title: For Sale:  Rare 1893 BSA Lee-Metford Rifle Boer War Unit-IDed
postcontent: the rifle features all original components, with all-matching serial numbers and truly excellent condition. Evidenced by the crispness of the markings on the metal, along with the original feathering of the wood grain and perfectly preserved BSA cartouche(rondelle) on the buttstock, the rifle shows no sign of refinish or restoration. A desirable find given the rifle's condition, its traceable history makes this rifle particularly rare. The upper tang of the buttstock is clearly marked with "V/2.WK", with the buttstock dated 1897. This identifies the rifle as having been issued to the 2nd Battalion of the Royal Warwickshire Regiment, with the "V" signifying either "Volunteers" or "Vth Division". This is significant as the 2nd Warwickshire Volunteers were assigned to the Vth(5th) Division under General Sir Charles Warren in 1899. Serving with distinction in the Boer War, the 2nd Warwickshires were involved in actions at the Cape Colony, Diamond Hill, and took heavy casualties in the advance on Koomati Poort(August, 1900). Prior to the Boer War, the 2nd Warwickshires were instrumental in the Sudan Campaign of 1896-1898, and they would go on to fame in the battlefields of France and Belgium during WWI.

The Shotgun Shoots Great, Everything Works Fine But At the Moment you can only have 2 Shells in the Gun- 1 in the chamber & 1 in the tube. It's an easy fix.  One of the Shell Latches(Right Latch if Looking from Front, Left if From Rear). This causes It to Not hold the Shotgun Shells In the Magazine Tube As It Should, you can fully load it with 6 Shells & they stay until you cycle the action to load the next Shell & the shells just come out since the Shell Latch isn't holding tension on the left side. If you load one in the chamber & one in the tube it works perfectly, It Simply Needs to be Adjusted or Possibly Re-Staked, which can be done at home for free. By chance if the Shell Latch needed to be replaced it's easy & the part(new shell Latch) is cheap, they're less than $20 & can easily be installed at home or a Gunsmith will do it for a small fee. To adjust or install you field strip the gun in 2 minutes & pop out the trigger group by removing 2 pins & adjust or replace the Shell Latch.
